  <div class="page-content">
    <h1>How to Diversify Your Portfolio Properly</h1>

    <p>Everyone has heard the age-old advice: <em>"Don't put all your eggs in one basket."</em> In finance, we call this <strong>diversification</strong>. But despite it being the most universally agreed-upon concept in investing, the majority of retail investors still fundamentally misunderstand how to execute it.</p>

    <p>Many beginners think that buying 20 different technology stocks means they are diversified. Others believe they need millions of dollars to build a properly balanced portfolio. Both assumptions are mathematically and practically wrong.</p>

    <p>In this guide, we are going to break down exactly what diversification is, how it works in the real world with real companies, and exactly how you can implement it today—whether you have $500 or $5,000,000. If you are entirely new to this, you might first want to read our primer on <a href="/what-is-a-portfolio">what is a portfolio</a>.</p>

    <h2>What is Diversification (In Plain English)?</h2>

    <p>Diversification is a risk management strategy that mixes a wide variety of investments within a portfolio. The rationale behind this technique is that a portfolio constructed of different kinds of assets will, on average, yield higher long-term returns and pose a lower risk of any individual holding or asset class destroying your wealth.</p>

    <p>Think of it as building a sports team. If you only draft star quarterbacks, your team will fail because no one is there to block, catch, or defend. You need players with different, non-correlated skill sets. In investing, you want assets that respond differently to the same economic events.</p>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <h3>The Two Types of Investment Risk</h3>
      <p>To understand why diversification works, you must understand what risks you are trying to mitigate:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Systematic Risk (Market Risk):</strong> This is the risk inherent to the entire market. Examples include recessions, interest rate hikes, or global pandemics. You <strong>cannot</strong> diversify away systematic risk using only stocks. When the entire economy contracts, almost everything drops.</li>
        <li><strong>Unsystematic Risk (Specific Risk):</strong> This is risk specific to a single company or industry. Examples include a CEO scandal at a specific firm, a new competitor destroying a business model, or a factory burning down. You <strong>can</strong> almost entirely eliminate unsystematic risk through diversification.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>How Diversification Actually Works in Practice</h2>

    <p>The magic of diversification lies in a concept called <strong>correlation</strong>. Correlation measures how investments move in relation to one another, on a scale of -1.0 to +1.0.</p>

    <ul>
      <li><strong>+1.0 (Perfectly Correlated):</strong> The assets move exactly together.</li>
      <li><strong>0.0 (Uncorrelated):</strong> The assets move completely independently of each other.</li>
      <li><strong>-1.0 (Negatively Correlated):</strong> The assets move in perfectly opposite directions.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>The goal is to hold assets that are not perfectly correlated. Let's look at a real-world example to illustrate this.</p>

    <h3>The "Illusion" of Diversification: A Real Example</h3>

    <p>Imagine Investor A decides to "diversify" their $10,000 by buying equal amounts of five stocks: Apple (AAPL), Microsoft (MSFT), Nvidia (NVDA), Alphabet (GOOGL), and Meta (META). They feel proud. They own five different massive, highly profitable businesses.</p>

    <p>But let's look at the reality. All five of these companies are U.S. large-cap technology/communications stocks. They all rely heavily on similar macro-economic factors (interest rates, consumer tech spending, digital advertising, AI adoption). Their correlation to one another is extremely high (often above 0.70 or 0.80).</p>

    <p>In 2022, when interest rates spiked and tech valuations contracted, look what happened to these specific stocks:</p>

