    <h3>The Misconception of "Diworsification"</h3>
    <p>Coined by legendary investor Peter Lynch, "diworsification" occurs when investors add more assets to their portfolio just for the sake of having more, effectively lowering their expected returns without meaningfully reducing risk.</p>
    <p>For example, buying five different S&P 500 index funds from five different brokerages does not make you 5x more diversified. You just own the exact same 500 stocks five times over, likely paying higher aggregate fees and making your life unnecessarily complicated.</p>

    <h3>The "Billionaire Exception" Misconception</h3>
    <p>You will often hear novices quote Warren Buffett: <em>"Diversification is protection against ignorance. It makes little sense if you know what you are doing."</em></p>
    <p>What beginners miss is the context. Buffett is a multi-billionaire who buys entire companies, installs his own management boards, and has teams of thousands of analysts. He is in the business of absolute control. You, buying fractional shares on a mobile app, have zero control over the companies you buy. Unless you are purchasing majority stakes in Fortune 500 companies, you need diversification.</p>


